2 TITL Notes on John Marshall
1 _OID 8e454448-0849-497a-96b4-166731e20e58
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;Source:&amp;nbsp; Wiley, Samuel T., &lt;em&gt;Biographical and Portrait Cyclopedia of Chester County, Pennsylvania&lt;/em&gt;, (Gresham Publishing Company, Richmond, Ind., 1893), 690&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&
2 CONC gt;The Marshall family of Chester county, ..., was founded by John Marshall, who emigrated about 1684 from Elton, in Derbyshire, England, and settled in Upper Darby township, Delaware county, and within the bounds of Darby Frieneds' Meeting, of whi
2 CONC ch he was a useful member.&amp;nbsp; He died September 13, 1729.&amp;nbsp; In 1688 he married Sarah Smith, of Darby, and their marriage was the first that was solemnized at the first meeting house built at that place.&amp;nbsp; Their children were:
2 CONC &amp;nbsp; John, William, and Thomas.&amp;nbsp; Thomas, the youngest, was born December 10, 1694, and settled in Concord township, Delaware county, where, in 1727, he built a brick house, which is still standing...On February 24, 1718, he married H
2 CONC annah Mendenhall, a sister to the wife of John Bartram, the eminent botanist.&amp;nbsp; Their son, Thomas Marshall, was born July 26, 1727, and married Edith Newlin, by whom he had four children, one son and three daughters.&amp;nbsp; The son, Thom
2 CONC as Marshall, Jr., was born December 12, 1756, and died August 13, 184, when in the eighty-eighth year of his age...On April 21, 1779, he married Mary Grubb, by whom he had several children, of whom the youngest was Samuel, who was born March 24, 17
2 CONC 89.&amp;nbsp; Samuel Marshall followed tanning and farming until his death, which occurred on August 27, 1882.&amp;nbsp; He...married Philena Pusey, a daughter of Ellis Pusey.&amp;nbsp; She was a preacher in the Society of Friends, and passed awa
2 CONC y in 1842.&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
